    {
        "content": "<p>My attempt: Trivially <code>up</code> is a surjective map.<br>\nby Cantor theorem, there is no surjective map from <code>U</code> to <code>Set U</code>. so it is sufficient to show that there is a surjective map from <code>Type</code> to <code>Set U</code>.</p>",
        "id": 456495507,
        "sender_full_name": "Asei Inoue",
        "timestamp": 1722851642
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here is one way:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">axiom</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">U</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- I want to assume `Type : Type` but</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Lean doesn't allow me to do so.</span>\n<span class=\"c1\">-- Then I will assume slightly weaker hypothesises...</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">axiom</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">down</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">U</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">axiom</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">up</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">u</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">U</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- There is a retract from Type to U</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">axiom</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">retract</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">up</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">down</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">-- I want to show this</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">paradox</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">False</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">not_small_type</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">range</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">down</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟨</span><span class=\"n\">Equiv</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">ofInjective</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">down</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">Function</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">LeftInverse</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">injective</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">retract</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">⟩⟩</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
